  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Fran\u00e7ois Massion\u2019s article, \"Terminology in the Age of AI: The Transformation of Terminology Theory and Practice,\" published in the Journal of Translation Studies, has achieved notable recognition within the academic community, reflected by its five citations across various scholarly venues.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Fran\u00e7ois Massion\u2019s exploration of terminology theory in the context of artificial intelligence has garnered a total of five citations, demonstrating its relevance and impact on the field. The article has been referenced in notable academic venues such as Tradum\u00e0tica tecnologies de la traducci\u00f3 and Lebende Sprachen, showcasing its influence across diverse disciplines related to translation studies.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The body of work illustrates the evolving landscape of terminology theory as shaped by advancements in AI technologies, reflecting a timely examination of how these developments challenge traditional practices. The citations from countries including Austria, Germany, and China indicate a geographic spread of interest and relevance, particularly in regions recognized for their contributions to translation research.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">While current metrics show no engagement on social media platforms or representations within community-based discourse, the academic citations themselves serve as critical markers of the article's significance. The lack of public mentions does not diminish the scholarly discussions that have arisen in academic circles, where the article's insights continue to inform research and dialogue.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The positive citation signals underline an established foundation that can support further inquiry into terminology practices influenced by AI. As the field of translation studies evolves, Massion\u2019s work stands as a pivotal reference, inviting scholars to reconsider and redefine the parameters of terminology amidst technological advancements.</p>",
